= card 'Spacing' do
  %p
    By default, headings and paragraphs have top margin of 16px and no bottom margin.
    As a general rule, is up to each element to decide how far it should be spaced from the content preceding it.
  %p first-child headings and p tags have 0 top margin.
  %p
    When you need closer spacing between a piece of text and the preceding content,
    use .mt-s (short for margin-top-small -- see utilities.sass).
    If you need no top margin, use .mt-0
  = haml_example do
    :plain
      %p I am a first-child element, so I have no top margin
      %p.mt-0 I have the .mt-0 class so I have no top margin
      %p.mt-s I have the .mt-s class so I have less top margin than normal
      %p I have normal top margin

= card 'Text Alignment' do
  %p there are utility classes for text alignment, vertical alignment, nowrap, and indenting
  = haml_example do
    :plain
      %p.text-right .text-right: right-aligned text
      %p.text-left .text-left left-aligned text
      %p.text-center .text-center center-aligned text
      %p
        %span.align-top .align-top: vertical-align top
        %span.align-middle ..align-middle vertical-align middle
      %p.indented .indented: indented 32px
      %p.nowrap .nowrap: white-space: nowrap

= card 'Weights' do
  = haml_example do
    :plain
      %p.normal-weight I am a p tag with the .normal-weight class
      %p.thin I am a p tag with the .thin class
